# üõ°Ô∏è Day 2 ‚Äì Linux Commands for Cybersecurity

---

## üìå 1. Basic Linux Commands

| Command          | Description                                 |
|------------------|---------------------------------------------|
| `pwd`            | Print current working directory             |
| `ls`             | List files and folders                      |
| `cd`             | Change directory                            |
| `mkdir`          | Create a new directory                      |
| `touch`          | Create an empty file                        |
| `rm`             | Remove file or directory                    |
| `cp`             | Copy files or directories                   |
| `mv`             | Move or rename files/directories            |
| `clear`          | Clears the terminal screen                  |
| `man [command]`  | Shows manual/help page for a command        |
| `history`        | Displays command history                    |

---

## üåê 2. Networking Commands

| Command                  | Description                                             |
|--------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------|
| `ip a` or `ifconfig`     | Shows IP address configuration                          |
| `ping [hostname/IP]`     | Tests network connectivity                              |
| `netstat -tuln`          | Lists open ports and listening services                 |
| `ss -tuln`               | Replacement for `netstat`, faster                       |
| `traceroute [host]`      | Shows route packets take to reach host                  |
| `nslookup [domain]`      | DNS lookup for domain names                             |
| `dig [domain]`           | Advanced DNS lookup tool                                |
| `curl [url]`             | Fetches content from a web address                      |
| `wget [url]`             | Downloads files from the internet                       |

---

## üõ†Ô∏è 3. Service and Log Commands

| Command                            | Description                                      |
|------------------------------------|--------------------------------------------------|
| `systemctl status [service]`       | Checks the status of a service                  |
| `systemctl start/stop/restart`     | Start/stop/restart a service                    |
| `journalctl`                       | Displays system logs (persistent logs)          |
| `journalctl -xe`                   | Shows logs for errors and warnings              |
| `tail -f /var/log/syslog`          | Real-time logs monitoring                       |
| `dmesg`                            | Kernel ring buffer messages                     |
| `who` / `w`                        | Shows who is logged into the system             |

---

## üñ•Ô∏è 4. System Administration Commands

| Command                      | Description                                        |
|------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------|
| `sudo [command]`             | Run command as superuser                          |
| `su`                         | Switch to root user                               |
| `adduser [username]`         | Add a new user                                    |
| `passwd [username]`          | Set or change user password                       |
| `chmod`                      | Change file/folder permissions                    |
| `chown`                      | Change file/folder ownership                      |
| `top` / `htop`               | Show running processes                            |
| `kill [PID]`                 | Kill a process by its ID                          |
| `df -h`                      | Shows disk usage                                  |
| `free -m`                    | Displays memory usage                             |
| `crontab -e`                 | Edit scheduled tasks (cron jobs)                  |

---

## üìÅ 5. Linux File System / Directories

| Directory        | Purpose                                                  |
|------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------|
| `/`              | Root directory ‚Äì top of the hierarchy                     |
| `/home/`         | User home directories                                     |
| `/bin/`          | Essential system binaries                                 |
| `/sbin/`         | System binaries (root/admin)                              |
| `/etc/`          | Configuration files                                       |
| `/var/`          | Variable files like logs, mail, spool                     |
| `/tmp/`          | Temporary files                                           |
| `/usr/`          | User-related programs and data                            |
| `/lib/`          | Shared system libraries                                   |
| `/dev/`          | Device files (e.g., hard drives, USBs)                    |
| `/proc/`         | Virtual filesystem for system info                        |

---


